'''Charles Edward Cannon''' (1884-1963), was a [[Great Britain|British]] [[jockey]].

He was [[Apprenticeship|apprenticed]] to his father, [[Tom Cannon, Sr.]], as a jockey at 14. He won the last race at [[Stockbridge Racecourse|Stockbridge]] in 1898 on Moon Wave. Charles enlisted in the [[19th Royal Hussars|19th Hussars]] Glocstershire regiment and was commissioned as [[Second Lieutenant]] in the [[World War I|first World War]]. He saw action in [[Ypres]], the [[Battle of the Somme|Somme]] and other campaigns. Cannon was shot in the head, buried alive, and received [[shell shock]] and [[mustard gas]] injuries, which he recovered in [[Netley Hospital|Netley]] in 1919. Before the war, Cannon was an accomplished pianist playing at the [[Royal Albert Hall]] for [[Edward VII|King Edward]].

Charles married Dorothy Thrush in 1916 and moved to West Wellow. They went had nine children named Tom, Peter, Margeret, Nina, Mornington, Joan, Sheila, Terence, and Patricia.

